With the increasing engagement with the SDGs among universities, the Times Higher Education (THE) Impact Rankings started to assess universitiesâ efforts towards achieving the 17 SDGs in 2019 (The Times Higher Education, 2022), while Elsevier provided many data to support the ranking. It is remarkable how the number of universities that participated in this ranking keeps increasing, from 467 universities from 74 countries/regions in 2019 to 1406 universities from 103 countries/regions in 2022 (Figure 1
                  ). The distribution of these universities is demonstrated in Figure 2
                  . In 2019, Japan, the United States, Russia, the United Kingdom, and Spain were the five countries with the most universities participating in the Impact Ranking (Supplementary Information 1). Turkey replaced the United States in 2020 among the top five, and India replaced Spain in the year after. In 2022, the countries with the most significant number of universities that disclosed their commitment to SDGs were Russia, Japan, Iran, Pakistan, India, and Turkey.
